# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldo-moro
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on Sunday 2 and also on Monday 3 June (but until noon) 1946.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] They were the first after World War II and elected 556 deputies to the Constituent Assembly.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Theoretically, a total of 573 deputies were to be elected, but the election did not take place in the Julian March and in South Tyrol, which were under military occupation by the United Nations.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] For the first time, Italian women were allowed to vote in a national election and run for a seat in the Constituent Assembly.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] This election was held concurrently with the 1946 Italian institutional referendum on the abolition of the monarchy.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] To emphasise the restoration of democracy after the fascist era, a pure party-list proportional representation was chosen.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Italian provinces were united in 31 constituencies, each electing a group of candidates.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] At constituency level, seats were divided between open lists using the largest remainder method with the Imperiali quota.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats were transferred at national level, where special closed lists of national leaders received the last seats using the Hare quota.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] At the end of World War II, Italy was governed under transitional laws as a result of agreements between the National Liberation Committee (CLN) and the royal Lieutenant General of the Realm Umberto II of Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] As no democratic elections had taken place for more than 20 years, legislative power was given to the government but, after the first election, the Italian Council of Ministers would have to receive a vote of confidence by the new Constituent Assembly.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] The three main contestants were Christian Democracy and the Italian Socialist Party, which had both received popular support before the fascist era, and the Italian Communist Party, which had strengthened itself with the armed struggle against Nazism and fascism during the war.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] The Italian Liberal Party, heir of the pre-fascist and conservative ruling class, proposed an alliance called National Democratic Union.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Monarchists groups created the National Bloc of Freedom, while the liberal socialist Action Party and Labour Democratic Party hoped to maximize the positive image of the governments that they ruled in the National Liberation Committee.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] The election gave a large majority to the government formed by the three leaders of the CLN, which was briefly joined by the Republican Party after the exile of Umberto II.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Together with the election, a constitutional referendum took place.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] Italian electors chose whether to continue the reign of Umberto II of Italy or turn Italy into a republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1946-italian-general-election] While all regions of northern Italy as far as Tuscany and Marches gave a majority to the republic, all regions of southern Italy to Lazio and Abruzzo voted to maintain the monarchy.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on 18 April 1948 to elect the first Parliament of the Italian Republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] As the last month of the election campaign began, *Time* published an article arguing that an FDP victory would push Italy to "the brink of catastrophe".
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The U.S. consequently intervened in the election by heavily funding the centrist coalition led by Christian Democracy (DC) and launching an anti-communist propaganda campaign in Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) claims that the Soviet Union responded by sending exorbitant funds to the FDP coalition; however, the PCI disputed this claim and expressed its discontent with what it perceived as a lack of support from the Soviets.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The DC won the election by a comfortable margin and defeated the FDP coalition.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The DC went on to form a government without the leftists, who had been expelled from the government coalition in the May 1947 crises and remained frozen out, and became the de facto ruling party of the First Italian Republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] It represented the start of the Italian party system of centrism that lasted until the 1960s when the PSI was allowed to join the government as part of the organic centre-left system.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The pure party-list proportional representation chosen two years before for the election of the Constituent Assembly was adopted for the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Italian provinces were divided into 31 constituencies, each electing a group of candidates.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] In each constituency, seats were divided between open lists using the largest remainder method with the Imperiali quota.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats transferred to the national level, where special closed lists of national leaders received the last seats using the Hare quota.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] For the Senate, 237 single-seat constituencies were created.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The candidates needed a two-thirds majority to be elected, but only 15 aspiring senators were elected this way.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] All remaining votes and seats were grouped in party lists and regional constituencies, where the D'Hondt method was used: Inside the lists, candidates with the best percentages were elected.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] This electoral system became standard in Italy, and was used until 1993.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The election remain unmatched in verbal aggression and fanaticism in Italy's period of democracy.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] According to the historian Gianni Corbi, the 1948 election was "the most passionate, the most important, the longest, the dirtiest, and the most uncertain electoral campaign in Italian history".
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The DC ran a campaign that pointed to the Communist coup in Czechoslovakia.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] It warned that in Communist countries "children send parents to jail", "children are owned by the state", and told voters that disaster would strike Italy if the Communists were to take power.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The FDP campaign focused on living standards and avoided embarrassing questions of foreign policy, such as United Nations membership (vetoed by the Soviet Union) and Communist Yugoslavia control of Trieste, or losing American financial and food aid through the Marshall Plan.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The PCI led the FDP coalition and had effectively marginalised the PSI, which suffered loss in terms of parliamentary seats and political power.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The PSI had also been hurt by the secession of a social-democratic faction led by Giuseppe Saragat, which contested the election with the concurrent list of Socialist Unity (US).
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The PCI had difficulties in restraining its more militant members, who in the period immediately after the war had engaged in violent acts of reprisals.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The 1948 general election was greatly influenced by the Cold War that was underway between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] After his defeat in the election, PCI leader Palmiro Togliatti stated on 22 April: "The elections were not free ...
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Brutal foreign intervention was used consisting of a threat to starve the country by withholding ERP aid if it voted for the Democratic Front ...
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The menace to use the atom bomb against towns or regions" that voted pro-communist.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The U.S. government's Voice of America radio began broadcasting anti-communist propaganda to Italy on 24 March 1948.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] By its own admission, the CIA gave US$1 million (equivalent to $13 million in 2025) to what they referred to as "center parties", and was accused of publishing forged letters to discredit the leaders of the PCI.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The National Security Act of 1947, which made foreign covert operations possible, had been signed into law about six months earlier by the U.S.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] U.S. agencies also sent ten million letters, made numerous short-wave radio broadcasts, and funded the publishing of books and articles, all of which warned Italians of the "consequences" of a Communist victory.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Overall, the U.S. funnelled $10 million to $20 million (equivalent to $130 million to $270 million in 2025) into the country for specifically anti-PCI purposes.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The CIA also made use of off-the-books sources of financing to interfere in the election: millions of dollars from the Economic Cooperation Administration affiliated with the Marshall Plan, and more than $10 million in captured Nazi money were steered to anti-communist propaganda.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] This was disputed by the PCI, which voiced its frustration at the Soviets' lack of support for the FDP's campaign.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Italian historian Alessandro Brogi dismisses the CIA's claims as "overexaggerated" and notes that the Soviets only undertook "ad hoc last minute diplomatic [and] financial action" because it feared that inaction in Italy would set a precedent for U.S. intervention in Eastern Europe.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Despite amicable meetings in the postwar years between top PCI official Pietro Secchia and Soviet leader Joseph Stalin, the Soviets were apprehensive about committing to Italy financially, and only provided "occasional and modest" funds to the PCI.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The DC eventually won the 1948 election with 48 per cent of the vote, and the FDP received 31 per cent.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The CIA's practice of influencing the political situation was repeated in every Italian election for at least the next 24 years.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] No left-leaning coalition won a general election until 1996.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] That was partly because of Italians' traditional bent for conservatism and even more importantly the Cold War, with the U.S. closely watching Italy in their determination to maintain a vital NATO presence amidst the Mediterranean and retain the Yalta-agreed *status quo* in Western Europe.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The Irish government, motivated by the country's devout Catholicism, also interfered in the election by funnelling the modern day equivalent of €2 million through the Irish Embassy to the Vatican, which then distributed it to Catholic politicians.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Joseph Walshe, Ireland's ambassador to the Vatican, had privately suggested secretly funding Azione Cattolica.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] The DC won a sweeping victory, taking 48.5 per cent of the vote and 305 seats in the Chamber of Deputies and 131 seats in the Senate of the Republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] With an absolute majority in both chambers of the Italian Parliament, Gasperi (the then DC leader and incumbent prime minister) could have formed a one-party government; however, he formed a centrist coalition with the Italian Liberal Party (PLI), the Italian Republican Party (PRI), and SU.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] De Gasperi formed three Council of Ministries during the parliamentary term, the second one in 1950 after the defection of the PLI who hoped for more rightist politics, and the third one in 1951 after the defection of the SU who hoped for more left-wing politics.
[src:aldo-moro/1948-italian-general-election] Following a provision of the new republican Constitution of Italy, all living democratic deputies elected during the 1924 Italian general election and deposed by the National Fascist Party (PNF) in 1926, automatically became members of the first republican Senate.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The **1953 Italian general election** was held in Italy on Sunday 7 June 1953.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The election was characterized by changes in the electoral law.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Even if the general structure remained uncorrupted, the government introduced a superbonus of two thirds of seats in the Chamber of Deputies for the coalition which would obtain at-large the absolute majority of votes.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The change was hugely opposed by the opposition parties as well as the smaller Christian Democracy's coalition partners, which had no realistic chances of success.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The new law was called "scam law" by its detractors, including some dissidents of minor government parties who founded special opposition groups to deny the artificial landslide to Christian Democracy.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In the 1950s, Italy became a founding member of the NATO alliance (1949), a member of the United Nations (1955) and an ally of the United States, which helped to revive the Italian economy through the Marshall Plan.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In the same years, Italy also became a founding member of the European Coal and Steel Community (1952) and of the European Economic Community (1957), later developed into the European Union.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] At the end of the 1950s an impressive economic growth was termed "Economic Miracle".
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Italian families used their newfound wealth to purchase consumer durables for the first time.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Between 1958 and 1965, the percentage of families owning a television rose from 12% to 49%, washing machines from 3% to 23%, and fridges from 13% to 55%.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Christian Democracy's main support areas, sometimes known as "vote tanks", were the rural areas in South, Center, and North-East Italy, whereas the industrial North-West had more left-leaning support because of the larger working class.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] An interesting exception were the "red regions" (Emilia-Romagna, Tuscany, and Umbria) where the Italian Communist Party has historically had a wide support.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] This is considered a consequence of the particular sharecropping ("mezzadria") farming contracts used in these regions.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Giovannino Guareschi wrote his novels about Don Camillo describing a village, Brescello, whose inhabitants are at the same time loyal to priest Camillo and communist mayor Peppone, who are fierce rivals.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In 1953, a Parliamentary Commission on poverty estimated that 24% of Italian families were either "destitute" or "in hardship", 21% of dwellings were overcrowded, 52% of homes in the South had no running drinking water, and only 57% had a lavatory.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In the 1950s, several important reforms were launched, such as agrarian reform (Scelba law), fiscal reform (Vanoni law), and the country enjoyed a period of economic boom and development (*miracolo economico*, or "economic miracle").
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In this period of time, a massive population transfer, from the impoverished South to the booming industrial North, took place.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] This exacerbated social contrasts, including between the old-established "worker aristocracy" and the new less qualified immigrants ("operaio-massa") of Southern origin.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] In addition, a wide gap between rich and poor continued to exist.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] By the end of the 1960s, it was estimated that 4 million Italians (out of a population of 54.5 million) were unemployed, underemployed, and casual labourers.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The complaint campaign of the oppositions against the "scam law" reached its goal.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The centrist coalition (DC, PSDI, PLI, PRI, SVP, and PSd'Az) won 49.9% of the national vote, coming just a few thousand votes short of the threshold for a two-thirds majority; the election resulted in an ordinary proportional distribution of the seats.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Minor dissident parties resulted determinant for the final result, especially the short-lived National Democratic Alliance.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] DC, the leading party, did not repeat the result of five years before, which had been obtained under special conditions linked to the Cold War, and lost a lot of votes to the right wing, which included resurgent Italian Fascist and neo-fascist politicians, particularly in Southern Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] While the government won the election with a clear working majority of seats in both houses, frustration at the failure to garner the expected supermajority caused big problems for the leading coalition.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Alcide De Gasperi was forced to resign by the Italian Parliament on August 2; he retired and died twelve months later.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The legislature continued with weak governments, with minor parties refusing institutional responsibilities.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Giuseppe Pella rose to power but fell after five months only following strong disputes about the status of the Free Territory of Trieste, which Pella was claiming.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] Amintore Fanfani not receiving a vote of confidence, Mario Scelba and Antonio Segni followed with more traditional centrist coalitions supported by the PSDI and the PLI; under the administration of the first one, the problem of Trieste was closed ceding Koper to Yugoslavia.
[src:aldo-moro/1953-italian-general-election] The parliamentary term was closed by the minority government chaired by Adone Zoli, finishing a legislature which hugely weakened the office of the Prime Minister, held by six different rulers.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The **1958 Italian general election** was held in Italy on 25 May 1958.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The number of MPs to be elected was calculated upon the population's size for the last time.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Minor changes were made to the electoral law in 1958, creating a system which would remain unchanged until its abrogation in 1993.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The pure party-list proportional representation was definitely adopted for the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Italian provinces were united in 32 constituencies, each electing a group of candidates.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] At constituency level, seats were divided between open lists using the largest remainder method with Imperiali quota.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats were transferred at national level, where they were divided using the Hare quota, and automatically distributed to best losers into the local lists.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] For the Senate, 237 single-seat constituencies were established, even if the assembly had 9 more members.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The candidates needed a landslide victory of two thirds of votes to be elected: only 5 hoping senators reached this goal.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] All remained votes and seats were grouped in party lists and regional constituencies, where a D'Hondt method was used: inside the lists, candidates with the best percentages were elected.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] After De Gasperi's retirement in 1953, Fanfani emerged as the anticipated successor, a role confirmed by his appointment as party secretary from 1954 to 1959.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] He reorganized and rejuvenated the national party organization of the Christian Democrats after the dependence on the church and the government which had typified the De Gasperi period.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Fanfani's activist and sometimes authoritarian style, as well as his reputation as an economic reformer, ensured that the moderates within the DC, who opposed the state's intrusion into the country's economic life, regarded him with distrust.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] His indefatigable energy and his passion for efficiency carried him far in politics, but he was rarely able to exploit fully the opportunities that he created.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] One politician once remarked: "Fanfani has colleagues, associates, acquaintances and subordinates.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The election gave similar results of five years before and, consequently, the same problems of political instability of the centrist formula.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Christian Democracy was polarized by a fraction which liked more leftist politics, and another one which urged for a rightist route.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Party's secretary Amintore Fanfani was in the first field, and called for a dialogue with the Italian Socialist Party, which had frozen its relationships with the Italian Communist Party after the Hungarian Revolution.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Fanfani led a year-term government, but the reaction of the conservative fraction gave the power to Antonio Segni, followed by Fernando Tambroni who received a decisive vote of confidence by the neo-fascist Italian Social Movement.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Strikes and revolts causing some casualties erupted through the country, and Tambroni had to resign.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] Fanfani returned to the premiership, this time with an openly centre-left programme supported by the socialist abstention.
[src:aldo-moro/1958-italian-general-election] The government created the middle school for workers' sons, and the ENEL after the electric energy nationalisation.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The **1963 Italian general election** was held in Italy on 28 April 1963.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] It was the first election with a fixed number of MPs to be elected, as decided by the second Constitutional Reform in February 1963.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The pure party-list proportional representation had traditionally become the electoral system for the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats were transferred at a national level, where they were divided using the Hare quota, and automatically distributed to best losers into the local lists.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] For the Senate, 237 single-seat constituencies were established, even if the assembly had risen to 315 members.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The candidates needed a landslide victory of two-thirds of votes to be elected, a goal which could be reached only by the German minorities in South Tirol.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] During the First Republic, the Christian Democracy slowly but steadily lost support, as society modernised and the traditional values at its ideological core became less appealing to the population.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Various options of extending the parliamentary majority were considered, mainly an opening to the left (*apertura a sinistra*), i.e. to the Socialist party (PSI), which after the 1956 events in Hungary had moved from a position of total subordination to the Communists, to an independent position.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Proponents of such a coalition proposed a series much-needed "structural reforms" that would modernize the country and create a modern social-democracy.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] In 1960, an attempt by the right wing of the Christian Democrats to incorporate the neo-fascist Italian Social Movement (MSI) in the Tambroni government led to violent and bloody riots (Genoa, Reggio Emilia), and was defeated.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Up until the Nineties, two types of governmental coalitions characterised the politics of post-war Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The first were “centrist” coalitions led by the Christian Democracy party together with smaller parties: the Social Democratic Party, the Republican Party, and the Liberal Party.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The first democratic government (1947) excluded both communists and the socialists, which brought about the political period known as “centrist government,” which ruled over Italian politics from 1948 to 1963.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The centre-left coalition (DC-PRI-PSDI-PSI) was the second type of coalition that characterised Italian politics, coming about in 1963 when the PSI (formerly the opposition party) went into government with the DC.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] This coalition lasted in parliament first for 12 years (from 1964 to 1976) and then with a revival in the Eighties that lasted until the start of the Nineties.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The Socialist Party entered government in 1963.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] During the first year of the new centre-left government, a wide range of measures were carried out which went some way towards the Socialist Party's requirements for governing in coalition with the Christian Democrats.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Urged on by the PSI, the government also made brave attempts to tackle issues relating to welfare services, hospitals, the agrarian structure, urban development, education, and overall planning.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] For instance, during the Centre-Left Government's time in office, social security was extended to previously uncovered categories of the population.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] In addition, entrance to university by examination was abolished in 1965.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Despite these important reforms, however, the reformist drive was soon lost, and the most important problems (including the mafia, social inequalities, inefficient state/social services, North/South imbalance) remained largely untackled.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] The election fell after the launch of the *centre-left* formula by the Christian Democracy, a coalition based upon the alliance with the Socialist Party which had left its alignment with the Soviet Union.
[src:aldo-moro/1963-italian-general-election] Some rightist electors abandoned the DC for the Liberal Party, which was asking for a centre-right government and received votes also from the quarrelsome monarchist area.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The **1964 Italian presidential election** was held in Italy from 16 to 28 December 1964, following the resignation of President Antonio Segni on 6 December 1964 due to health problems.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Only members of Parliament and regional delegates were entitled to vote, most of these electors having been elected in the 1963 general election.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] As head of state of the Italian Republic, the President has a role of representation of national unity and guarantees that Italian politics comply with the Italian Constitution, in the framework of a parliamentary system.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Only on the twenty-first round of voting Giuseppe Saragat, the leader of Italian Democratic Socialist Party and former President of the Constituent Assembly, was finally elected President.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Saragat was the first left-wing politician to become President of the Republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] In accordance with the Italian Constitution, the election was held in the form of a secret ballot, with the Senators and the Deputies entitled to vote.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The election was held in the Palazzo Montecitorio, home of the Chamber of Deputies, with the capacity of the building expanded for the purpose.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The first three ballots required a two-thirds majority of the 963 voters in order to elect a president, or 642 votes.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Starting from the fourth ballot, an absolute majority was required for candidates to be elected, or 482 votes.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The presidential mandate lasts seven years.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The election was presided over by the President of the Chamber of Deputies Brunetto Bucciarelli-Ducci, who proceeded to the public counting of the votes, and by the Vice president of the Senate Ennio Zelioli-Lanzini, since President Cesare Merzagora was serving as acting President of the Republic.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] During summer 1964 the so-called *Piano Solo* prepared by general Giovanni De Lorenzo was conceived to make a coup d'état and overthrow the first centre-left government led by Aldo Moro.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The coup was stopped before taking place, as the Italian Socialist Party agreed to reduce its more radical reformist claims.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] However, on 7 August 1964, during a heated discussion with the Prime Minister Moro and the leader of the Italian Democratic Socialist Party Giuseppe Saragat, President Antonio Segni suffered a serious cerebral hemorrhage in his office at the Quirinal Palace.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] He only partially recovered and decided to resign on 6 December 1964, citing health matters.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Cesare Merzagora, as President of the Senate, became the acting President of the Republic till a new presidential election was called.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] On 16 December 1964, the Italian Parliament convened to elect the new President after just two years since last presidential election occurred.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] The official candidate of Christian Democracy was the former president of the Chamber of Deputies Giovanni Leone, whose candidacy was immediately contrasted by the former Prime Minister Amintore Fanfani, preferred by the left-wing faction of the party.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] As they did two years before, communists sustained again Umberto Terracini, while socialists decided to vote for the democratic socialist leader Giuseppe Saragat.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] As the count advanced, both Leone and Fanfani decided to retire from the race, while socialists and communists found a common ground on the candidacy of the socialist leader and Deputy Prime Minister Pietro Nenni.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] Christian Democracy couldn't sustain Nenni since it'd have been meant to vote for a candidate voted by the communists themselves and thus finding the opposition of the more conservative social groups of the country.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] After almost twenty rounds of voting, Christian Democracy decided to not oppose Saragat, a name then married also by socialists and communists.
[src:aldo-moro/1964-italian-presidential-election] On the twenty-first ballot and after almost two weeks of voting, Giuseppe Saragat was finally elected President by a large margin and sworn in on 29 December 1964.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The **1968 Italian general election** was held in Italy on 19 May 1968.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The Christian Democracy (DC) remained stable around 38% of the votes.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] They were marked by a victory of the Communist Party (PCI) passing from 25% of 1963 to c.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] 30% at the Senate, where it presented jointly with the new Italian Socialist Party of Proletarian Unity (PSIUP), which included members of the Socialist Party (PSI) which disagreed the latter's alliance with DC.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The Socialist Party and the Democratic Socialist Party (PSDI) presented together as the Unified PSI–PSDI, but gained c.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] 15%, far less than the sum of what the two parties had obtained separately in 1963.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats were transferred at national level, where they was divided using the Hare quota, and automatically distributed to best losers into the local lists.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The candidates needed a landslide victory of two thirds of votes to be elected, a goal which could be reached only by the German minorities in South Tirol.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] On 21 August 1964, the historic leader of the Italian Communist Party, Palmiro Togliatti died of cerebral haemorrhage while vacationing with his companion Nilde Iotti in Yalta, then in the Soviet Union.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] According to some of his collaborators, Togliatti was travelling to the Soviet Union in order to give his support to Leonid Brezhnev's election as Nikita Khrushchev's successor at the head of Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Togliatti was replaced by Luigi Longo, a long-time prominent PCI member; Longo continued Togliatti's line, known as the "Italian road to Socialism", playing down the alliance between the Italian Communist Party and the USSR.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] He reacted without hostility to the new left movements that sprang up in 1968 and, among the leaders of the PCI, was one of those most disposed to engage with the new activists, although he did not condone their excesses.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Moreover, Francesco De Martino, became the new Secretary of the Italian Socialist Party, after the resignation of Pietro Nenni, due to age.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] In 1965, the SIFAR intelligence agency was transformed into the SID following an aborted coup d'état, *Piano Solo*, which was to give power to the Carabinieri, at that time headed by general De Lorenzo.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The difficult equilibrium of Italian society was challenged by a rising left-wing movement, in the wake of 1968 student unrest ("Sessantotto").
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] This movement was characterized by such heterogeneous events as revolts by jobless farm workers (Avola, Battipaglia 1969), occupations of Universities by students, social unrest in the large Northern factories (1969 *autunno caldo*, hot autumn).
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Social protests, in which the student movement was particularly active, shook Italy during the 1969 *autunno caldo* (Hot Autumn), leading to the occupation of the Fiat factory in Turin.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The election was a test for the new organization of the socialist area, which was divided between the new revolutionary and Communist-allied Italian Socialist Party of Proletarian Unity and the governmental social-democratic federation between PSI and PSDI.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The polls said that the split of the PSIUP in 1964 had not been a purely parliamentary operation, but the reflex of divisions into the leftist electorate.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] The result shocked the PSI's leadership, causing the sudden sinking of the social-democratic federation, and an alternance of provisional retirements by the government, firstly led by lifetime senator Giovanni Leone and then, through two political crisis, by DC's secretary Mariano Rumor.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Unsuccessfully trying to recover its lost leftist electors, the PSI returned to the alliance with the PCI for the regional elections of 1970, so causing another crisis and a new change of premiership, then led by Emilio Colombo, but the government coalition had continuous problems of instability.
[src:aldo-moro/1968-italian-general-election] Influent Giulio Andreotti tried to resurrect the centrist formula in 1972, but he failed, opening the way to the first early election of the republican history.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro served as Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs from May 1969 to July 1972 and again from July 1973 to November 1974.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his ministry, he implemented a pro-Arab policy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He was Italy's Minister of Justice and of Public Education during the 1950s.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] From March 1959 until January 1964, he served as secretary of the DC.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 16 March 1978, he was kidnapped by the far-left terrorist group Red Brigades; he was killed after 55 days of captivity.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro was one of Italy's longest-serving post-war prime ministers, leading the country for more than six years.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro implemented a series of social and economic reforms that modernized the country.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Due to his accommodation with the Italian Communist Party leader Enrico Berlinguer, known as the Historic Compromise, Moro is widely considered to be one of the most prominent fathers of the modern Italian centre-left.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Aldo Romeo Luigi Moro was born on 23 September 1916 in Maglie, near Lecce, into a family from Ugento in the Apulia region of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] His father, Renato Moro, was a school inspector, while his mother, Fida Sticchi, was a teacher.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] At the age of 4, he moved with his family to Milan; they soon moved back to Apulia, where he gained a classical high school degree at Archita lyceum in Taranto.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] There, he studied law at the University of Bari and graduated in 1939.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After graduation, he became a professor of philosophy of law and colonial policy (1941) and of criminal law (1942) at the University of Bari.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1935, Moro joined the Italian Catholic Federation of University Students (FUCI) of Bari.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1939, under the approval of Giovanni Battista Montini, the future Pope Paul VI, whom he had befriended, Moro was chosen as president of the association.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He kept the post until 1942 when he was forced to fight in World War II and was succeeded by Giulio Andreotti, who at the time was a law student from Rome.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his university years, Italy was ruled by the fascist regime of Benito Mussolini, and Moro took part in student competitions known as Lictors of Culture and Art organized by the local fascist students' organization, the University Fascist Groups.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1943, along with other Catholic students, he founded the periodical *La Rassegna*, which was published until 1945.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] It served as inspiration and guideline for the economic policy of the future Christian democrats.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1945, he married Eleonora Chiavarelli (1915–2010), with whom he had four children: Maria Fida (born 1946), Anna (born 1949), Agnese (born 1952), and Giovanni (born 1958).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1963, Moro was transferred to La Sapienza University of Rome as a professor of the institutions of law and criminal procedure.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro developed his interest in politics between 1943 and 1945.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Initially, he seemed to be very interested in the social-democratic component of the Italian Socialist Party (PSI) but then started cooperating with other Christian-democratic politicians in opposition to the Italian fascist regime.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During these years, he met Alcide De Gasperi, Mario Scelba, Giovanni Gronchi, and Amintore Fanfani.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 19 March 1943, the group reunited in the house of Giuseppe Spataro and officially formed the Christian Democracy (DC) party.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the DC, he joined the left-wing faction led by Giuseppe Dossetti, of whom he became a close ally.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1945, he became director of the magazine *Studium* and president of the Graduated Movement of Catholic Action (*Azione Cattolica*, AC), a widespread Catholic lay association.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After being appointed vice-president of the DC, Moro was elected in the 1946 Italian general election a member of the Constituent Assembly of Italy, where he took part in the work to redact the Italian Constitution.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] It was during this period that his relations with the Italian Socialist Democratic Party (PSDI) and Italian social-democrats began.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1946, Moro ran for the Bari–Foggia constituency, where he received nearly 28,000 votes.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the 1948 Italian general election, he was elected with 63,000 votes to the newly formed Chamber of Deputies, and was appointed Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs in the fifth De Gasperi government from 23 May 1948 to 27 January 1950.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After Dossetti's retirement in 1952, Moro founded, along with Antonio Segni, Emilio Colombo, and Mariano Rumor, the Democratic Initiative faction, which was led by his old friend Fanfani.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the 1953 Italian general election, Moro was re-elected to the Chamber of Deputies, where he held the position of chairman of the DC parliamentary group.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1955, was appointed as Italian Minister of Grace and Justice in the first Segni government led by Segni as Prime Minister of Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1956, he was among the most popular candidates, receiving the most votes during the party's congress.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In May 1957, the PSDI withdrew its support to the government and Segni resigned on 6 May 1957.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 20 May 1957, Adone Zoli was sworn in as the new head of government and Moro was appointed Italian Minister of Education.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After the 1958 Italian general election, Zoli resigned.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 1 July 1958, Fanfani was sworn in as the new prime minister at the head of a coalition government with the PSDI and case-by-case support by the Italian Republican Party (PRI).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro was confirmed as the head of Italian education and remained in office until February 1959.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his tenure, he introduced the study of civic education in schools.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In March 1959, after Fanfani's resignation as prime minister, a new congress was called.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The leaders of the Democratic Initiative faction reunited themselves in the Convent of Dorothea of Caesarea, where they abandoned the leftist policies promoted by Fanfani and founded the *Dorotei* (Dorotheans) faction.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the party's national council, Moro was elected secretary of the DC and was then confirmed in the October's congress held in Florence.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The 1963 Italian general election was characterized by a lack of consensus for the DC; in fact, the election was held after the launch of the centre-left formula by the DC, a coalition based upon the alliance with the PSI, which had left their alignment with the Soviet Union.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Some rightist electors abandoned the DC for the Italian Liberal Party (PLI), which was asking for a centre-right government and received votes also from the quarrelsome monarchist area.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro refused the office of prime minister, preferring to provisionally maintain his more influential post at the head of the party.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Initially, the DC decided to replace Fanfani with a provisional administration led by an impartial president of the Chamber of Deputies, Giovanni Leone.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] When the congress of the PSI in autumn authorized a full engagement of the party into the government, Leone resigned and Moro became the new prime minister.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro's first government was unevenly supported by the DC but also by the PSI, along with the PSDI and the Italian Republican Party (PRI).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The coalition, which replaced the previous Centrism system, was known as the Organic centre-left and was characterized by consociationalist and social corporatist tendencies.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During Moro's premiership, a wide range of social reforms was carried out.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This included the 1967 Bridge Law (*Legge Ponte*).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] A bill approved on 21 July 1965 extended the program of social security.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Despite mistrust and opposition, particularly when the Italian economic miracle came to an end and the government had to control the rise of inflation, the reforms continued.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Two 1966 laws provided traders with insurance.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his premiership, Moro had to face the outcome of one of the most tragic events in Italian republican history, the Vajont Dam disaster.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 9 October 1963, a few weeks before his oath as prime minister, a landslide occurred on Monte Toc, in the province of Pordenone.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The landslide caused a megatsunami in the artificial lake in which 50 million cubic metres of water overtopped the dam in a wave of 250 metres (820 ft), leading to the complete destruction of several villages and towns, and 1,917 deaths.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Immediately after the disaster, government and local authorities insisted on attributing the tragedy to an unexpected and unavoidable natural event.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Numerous warnings, signs of danger, and negative appraisals had been disregarded in the previous months and the eventual attempt to safely control the landslide into the lake by lowering its level came when the landslide was almost imminent and was too late to prevent it.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The PCI newspaper *L'Unità* was the first to denounce the actions of management and government.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The DC accused the PCI of political profiteering from the tragedy, promising to bring justice to the people killed in the disaster.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Differently from Leone, who was his predecessor and became the head of SADE's team of lawyers, Moro acted strongly to condemn the managers of the society.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He immediately dismissed the administrative officials who had supervised the construction of the dam.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 25 June 1964, the government was beaten on the budget law for the Italian Ministry of Education concerning the financing of private education.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During the presidential consultations for the formation of a new cabinet, Segni, the then moderate DC member and president of Italy, asked the PSI leader Pietro Nenni to exit from the government majority.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 16 July 1964, Segni sent the *Carabinieri* general Giovanni de Lorenzo to a meeting of representatives of DC, in order to deliver a message in case the negotiations around the formation of a new centre-left government would fail.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to some historians, De Lorenzo reported that Segni was ready to give a subsequent mandate to the president of the Senate of the Republic, Cesare Merzagora, and would ask him to form a president's government composed by all the conservative forces in the Italian Parliament.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This attempted coup, which came to be known as the *Piano Solo*, only became public in 1967 through the investigative reporting of *L'Espresso*.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Ultimately, Moro managed to form another centre-left majority.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During the negotiations, Nenni had accepted the downsizing of his reform programs.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 17 July 1964, Moro went to the Quirinal Palace, with the acceptance of the assignment and the list of ministers of his second government.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In August 1964, Segni had a serious cerebral haemorrhage and resigned after a few months.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the 1964 Italian presidential election, which was held in December, Moro and his majority tried to elect a leftist politician at the Quirinal Palace.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On the twenty-first round of voting, the leader of the PSDI and former president of the Constituent Assembly, Giuseppe Saragat, was elected with 646 votes out of 963.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Saragat was the first left-wing politician to become president of Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The PSI and PSDI ran in a joint list named Unified Socialist Party (PSU), which lost many votes compared to the previous election, while the PCI gained ground, achieving 30% of votes in the Senate.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The PSI and PSDI decided to exit from the government and Saragat appointed Leone at the head of the new cabinet composed only by DC members.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the 1968 DC congress, Moro yielded the secretariat and passed to internal opposition.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 5 August 1969, he was appointed Italian Minister of Foreign Affairs by the then prime minister Mariano Rumor, a position that he also held under the premierships of Emilio Colombo and Giulio Andreotti.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his ministry, Moro continued the pro-Arab policy of his predecessor Fanfani.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He forced Yasser Arafat to promise not to carry out terrorist attacks in Italian territory, with a commitment that was known as the Moro pact (*lodo Moro*).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The existence of this pact and its validity was confirmed by Bassam Abu Sharif, a long-time leader of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Interviewed by Italian newspapers, such as *Corriere della Sera* and *La Stampa*, he confirmed the existence of an agreement between Italy and the PFLP, thanks to which the PFLP could "transport weapons and explosives, guaranteeing immunity from attacks in return".
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] About the pact, Abu Sharif commented: "I personally followed the negotiations for the agreement.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Aldo Moro was a great man, a true patriot, who wanted to save Italy some headaches, but I never met him.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] We discussed the details with an admiral and agents of the Italian secret service.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The agreement was defined and since then we have always respected it; we were allowed to organize small transits, passages, and purely Palestinian operations, without involving Italians.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After the deal, every time I came to Rome, two cars were waiting for me to protect myself.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] For our part, we also guaranteed to avoid embarrassment to your country, that is attacks which started directly from the Italian soil." This version was confirmed by former president Francesco Cossiga, who stated that Moro was the real and only creator of the pact.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro also had to cope with the difficult situation which erupted following the coup by Muammar Gaddafi in Libya, a very important country for Italian interests not only for colonial ties but also for its energy resources and the presence of about 20,000 Italians.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the 1971 Italian presidential election, Fanfani was proposed as the DC candidate for the office.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] His candidacy was weakened by the divisions within his own party and the candidacy of the PSI member Francesco De Martino, who received votes from PCI, PSI, and some PSDI members.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Fanfani retired after several unsuccessful ballots and Moro was then proposed as a candidate by the left-wing faction.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The right-wing strongly opposed him and the moderate conservative Leone was slightly preferred to him.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] At the twenty-third round, Leone was finally elected with a centre-right majority, with 518 votes out of 996, including those of the MSI.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 4 August 1974, a bomb exploded on the Italicus Express, killing 12 people and injuring 48.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The train was travelling from Rome to Munich; having left Florence about 45 minutes earlier, it was approaching the end of the long San Benedetto Val di Sambro tunnel under the Apennines.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The bomb had been placed in the fifth passenger carriage and exploded at 01:23, while the train was reaching the end of the tunnel.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The effects of the explosion and subsequent fire would have been even more terrible if the train had remained inside the tunnel.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to what his daughter Maria Fida stated in 2004, Moro should have been on board.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] A few minutes before departure, he was joined by some officials of the ministry who made him get off to sign some important documents.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to some reconstructions, Moro would have been the real target of the Italicus Express bombing.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In October 1974, Rumor resigned as prime minister after failing to come to an agreement on how to deal with rising economic inflation.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In November, Leone gave Moro the task of forming a new cabinet; he was sworn in on 23 November 1974, at the head a cabinet composed by DC and PRI, and externally supported by PSI and PSDI.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During Moro's second term as prime minister, the government implemented a series of other important social reforms.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] A bill, approved on 3 June 1975, introduced various changes for pensioners.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his premiership, Moro signed the Osimo Treaty with the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, defining the official partition of the Free Territory of Trieste.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The port city of Trieste with a narrow coastal strip to the northwest (Zone A) was given to Italy, while a portion of the north-western part of the Istrian peninsula (Zone B) was given to Yugoslavia.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The Italian government was harshly criticized for signing the treaty, particularly for the secretive way in which negotiations were carried out, skipping the traditional diplomatic channels.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Since Istria had been an ancient Italian region, dating back to Roman Italy, together with the Venetian region of the Roman Empire, as *Venetia et Histria*, Italian nationalists of the MSI rejected the idea of giving it up.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Between World War I and the end of World War II, Istria had belonged to Italy for twenty-five years, and the west coast of Istria had long had a sizeable Italian minority population.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Despite the tensions within the government's majority, the close relations between Moro and the PCI leader Enrico Berlinguer guaranteed a certain stability to Moro's governments, allowing them a capacity to act that went beyond the premises that had seen them born.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The fourth Moro government, with Ugo La Malfa as Deputy Prime Minister of Italy, started the first dialogue with the PCI, with the aim of beginning a new phase to strengthen the Italian democratic system.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1976, the PSI secretary Francesco De Martino withdrew the external support to the government and Moro was forced to resign.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After the 1976 Italian general election, the PCI gained a historic 34% votes and Moro became a vocal supporter of the necessity of starting a dialogue between DC and PCI.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro's main aim was to widen the democratic base of the government, including the PCI in the parliamentary majority, in which the cabinets should have been able to represent a larger number of voters and parties.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to him, the DC should have been at the centre of a coalition system based on the principles of consociative democracy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This process was known as Historic Compromise.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Between 1976 and 1977, Berlinguer's PCI broke with the Communist Party of the Soviet Union, implementing, together with the Spanish and French Communist parties, a new political theory and strategy known as Eurocommunism.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Such a move made eventual cooperation more acceptable for DC voters, and the two parties began an intense parliamentary debate in a moment of deep social crises.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 1977, Moro was personally involved in international disputes.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He strongly defended Rumor during the parliamentary debate on the Lockheed scandal, and some journalists reported that Moro himself might have been involved in the bribery.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The allegation, with the aim of politically destroying Moro and avoiding the risk of a DC–PCI–PSI cabinet, failed when Moro was cleared on 3 March 1978, thirteen days before his kidnapping.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The early 1978 proposal by Moro of starting a cabinet composed of DC and PSI members, externally supported by the PCI was strongly opposed by both superpowers of the Cold War era.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The United States feared that the cooperation between PCI and DC might have allowed the PCI to gain information on strategic NATO military plans and installations.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moreover, the participation in the government of communists in a Western country would have represented a cultural failure for the United States.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On the other hand, the Soviets considered the potential participation by the PCI in a cabinet as a form of emancipation from Moscow and rapprochement to the Americans.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 16 March 1978, on via Fani, in Rome, a unit of the militant far-left organization known as Red Brigades (BR) blocked the two-car convoy that was carrying Moro and kidnapped him, murdering his five bodyguards.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On the day of his kidnapping, Moro was on his way to a session of the Chamber of Deputies, where a discussion was to take place regarding a vote of confidence for a new government led by Andreotti, that would for the first time have the support of the PCI.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] It was to be the first implementation of Moro's strategic political vision.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Additionally, he was considered to be the frontrunner for the 1978 Italian presidential election.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In the following days, trade unions called for a general strike, while security forces made hundreds of raids in Rome, Milan, Turin, and other cities searching for Moro's location, as places linked to Moro and the kidnapping became centres of minor pilgrimage.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] An estimated 16 million Italians took part in the mass public demonstrations.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After a few days, even Pope Paul VI, a close friend of Moro's, intervened, offering himself in exchange for Moro.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Despite the 13,000 police officers mobilized, 40,000 house searches, and 72,000 roadblocks, the police did not carry out any arrests.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The event has been compared to the assassination of John F.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Kennedy, and referred to as Italy's 9/11.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Although Italy was not the sole European country to experience terrorism, the list including France, Germany, Ireland, and Spain, the murder of Moro was the apogee of Italy's Years of Lead.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Many details of Moro's kidnapping remain heavily disputed and unknown.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Alternative theories gained traction with the institution of a special inquiring committee by the Italian Parliament in 2014 that concluded its operations in 2018.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The committee concluded that the judicial truth was produced on the basis of the confession of the terrorist Valerio Morucci and that other evidence which contradicted his version was downplayed.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In August 2020, about sixty individuals from the world of historical research and political inquiry signed a document denouncing the growing weight that the conspiratorial view on the kidnapping and killing of Moro has in public discourse.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The Red Brigades proposed exchanging Moro's life for the freedom of several prisoners.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] There has been speculation that during his detention many government officials, including the then interior minister Francesco Cossiga, knew where he was being held.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Italian politicians were divided into two factions: one favourable to negotiation (*linea del negoziato*) and the other totally opposing the idea of a negotiated settlement (*linea della fermezza*).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The government immediately took a hardline position, namely that the state must not bend to terrorist demands.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This position was openly criticized by prominent DC party members, such as Amintore Fanfani and Giovanni Leone, who at the time was serving as president of Italy.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] All major political forces followed this hardline stance.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This included the PCI, which supported democracy and was part of the Italian Parliament; the PCI was accused by the Red Brigades of being a pawn of the bourgeoisie.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Exceptions were the Italian Socialist Party led by Bettino Craxi and the extra-parliamentary left.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 2 April 1978, Romano Prodi, Mario Baldassarri, and Alberto Clò, three professors of the University of Bologna, passed on a tip about a safe-house where the Red Brigades might be holding Moro.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Prodi stated he had been given the tip by the DC founders from beyond the grave in a séance through the use of a Ouija board, which gave the names of Viterbo, Bolsena, and Gradoli.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During the investigation of Moro's kidnapping, some members of law enforcement in Italy and of the secret services advocated for the use of torture against terrorists; prominent military members and generals, such as Carlo Alberto dalla Chiesa, were against this.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] During his kidnapping, Moro wrote several letters to the DC leaders and to Pope Paul VI.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Some of those letters, including one that was very critical of Andreotti, were kept secret for more than a decade and published only in the early 1990s.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In his letters, Moro said that the state's primary focus should be saving lives and that the government should comply with his kidnappers' demands.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Most of the DC's leaders argued that the letters did not express Moro's genuine wishes, arguing they were written under duress, and thus refused all negotiations.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This position was held in stark contrast to the requests of Moro's family.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In his appeal to the terrorists, Pope Paul VI asked them to release Moro "without conditions".
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The specified "without conditions" is controversial; according to some sources, it was added to Paul VI's letter against his will, and that the Pope wanted to negotiate with the kidnappers to secure the safety of Moro.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to Antonio Mennini, Pope Paul VI had saved ₤10 billion (equivalent to almost $60 million in 2026) to pay a ransom in order to save Moro.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] When it became clear that the government would continue to refuse to negotiate, the Red Brigades held a summary trial, known as "the people's trial", in which Moro was found guilty and sentenced to death.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] They then sent a last demand to the Italian authorities, stating that if 16 Red Brigades prisoners were not released, Moro would be killed.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The Italian authorities responded with a large-scale manhunt, which was unsuccessful.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 7 May 1978, Moro sent a farewell letter to his wife.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 9 May 1978, after 55 days of captivity, the terrorists placed Moro in a car and told him to cover himself with a blanket, saying that they were going to transport him to another location.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After Moro was covered, they shot him ten times.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to the official reconstruction after a series of trials, the killer was Mario Moretti.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Moro's body was left in the trunk of a red Renault 4 on Via Michelangelo Caetani towards the Tiber River near the Roman Ghetto.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] After the recovery of Moro's body, Cossiga resigned as interior minister.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Pope Paul VI personally officiated at Moro's funeral mass.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] On 23 January 1983, an Italian court sentenced 32 members of the BR to life imprisonment for their role in the kidnapping and murder of Moro, among other crimes.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Many elements and facts have never been fully cleared up, despite a series of trials, and this led to a number of other alternative theories about the events to become popularized.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Andreotti underwent a trial for his role in the assassination of Pecorelli.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He was acquitted in the first instance trial (1999), convicted in the second (2002), and acquitted by Italy's Supreme Court of Cassation (2003).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In a 2012 interview with Ulisse Spinnato Vega of Agenzia Clorofilla, the BR co-founders Alberto Franceschini and Renato Curcio remembered Pecorelli.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Franceschini stated: "Pecorelli, before dying, said that both the United States and the Soviet Union wanted Moro's death." Additionally, that Moro was suffering from Stockholm syndrome was questioned by the two reports of the Italian Parliament's inquiry about the Moro affair.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to this view, Moro was at the height of his faculties, he was very recognizable, and at some point it was he who was leading the negotiation for his own liberation and salvation.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This position was supported by Leonardo Sciascia, who discussed it in the minority report he signed as a member of the first parliamentary commission and in his book *L'affaire Moro*.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 2005, Sergio Flamigni, a leftist politician and writer who had served on a parliamentary inquiry on the Moro case, suggested the involvement of the Operation Gladio network directed by NATO.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He asserted that Gladio had manipulated Moretti as a way to take over the Red Brigades to effect a strategy of tension aimed at creating popular demand for a new, right-wing law-and-order regime.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In 2006, Steve Pieczenik was interviewed by Emmanuel Amara in his documentary film *Les derniers jours d'Aldo Moro* ("The Last Days of Aldo Moro").
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to him, the decision to have Moro killed was taken during the fourth week of his detention, when Moro was thought to be revealing state secrets in his letters, namely the existence of Gladio.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In another interview, Cossiga revealed that the Crisis Committee had also leaked, in a form of black propaganda, a false statement attributed to the Red Brigades that Moro was already dead.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] This was intended to communicate to the kidnappers that further negotiations would be useless since the government had written Moro off.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] As a Christian democrat with social-democratic tendencies, Moro is widely considered one of the ideological fathers of modern Italian centre-left, having led the first centre-left government in the history of the Italian Republic, the Organic centre-left.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] He was the leading figure of the left wing of the DC, which he steered towards the left as the party's secretary-general from 1959 to 1964.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] While he was prime minister, a land reform was implemented in 1964; it has been described as the first step towards abolishing sharecropping (Mezzadria).
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Landless tenants were given cheap credit in order to allow them to own the land.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Economically, Moro's policies are seen as a response to socialist influence.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Although central planning instruments were never used, a five-year economic programme was established in 1965.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Due to his reformist stances but also for his tragic death, Moro has often been compared to John F.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] According to media reports on 26 September 2012, the Holy See received a file on beatification for Moro; this is the first step to becoming a saint in the Catholic Church.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In April 2015, it was reported that the process of beatification might be suspended or closed following the recent controversies.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The postulator stated that the process would continue when the discrepancies were cleared up.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] The halting of proceedings was due to Mennini, the priest who heard his last confession, being allowed to provide a statement to a tribunal in regards to Moro's kidnapping and confession.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] Following this, the beatification process was resumed.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] In January 2022, a note claiming responsibility for the abduction of Moro was auctioned despite widespread condemnation.
[src:aldo-moro/aldo-moro] A number of films have portrayed the events of Moro's kidnapping and murder with varying degrees of fictionalization.
